[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1884 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished fifth in the American Association with a record of 68–41, 8 games behind the New York Metropolitans.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were looking to return to their 1882 form, when they won the American Association pennant before falling to third place in 1883.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club named pitcher Will White the player-manager for the 1884 season, taking over for catcher Pop Snyder.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season, although they did sign Tom Mansell, who had split the previous season between the Detroit Wolverines of the National League, and the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns of the AA, hitting .305 with 34 RBI and 45 runs between those two teams.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club also moved into American Park for the 1884 season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly was the offensive force on the team, hitting .339 with eleven home runs and 91 RBI, all club highs.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones hit .314 with seven home runs and 71 RBI, along with a team high 117 runs.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White led the way with a 34–18 record and a 3.32 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati got off to a slow start, as they lost their first game in their new ballpark, 10–9 to the Columbus Buckeyes, and they had a record of 4–5 in their first nine games, before reeling off four wins in a row to stay above the .500 level for the rest of the season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got red hot, as they eventually had a 28–14 record, only one game out of first place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] In a three-game series against the Washington Nationals, the Red Stockings outscored their opposition 48–6.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started to fade as the season continued on, and with their record at 44–27 changed managers, bringing Pop Snyder back as player-manager.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati continued to slump, falling to 10½ games out of first place with a 52–35 record, but then won ten games in a row to climb back to within 4½ games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was too little too late though, as Cincinnati finished the season with a 68–41 record, good enough for fifth place, eight games behind the Metropolitans.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1885 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished second in the American Association, 16 games behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the Red Stockings hired O.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Caylor to become the manager of the team, the first time in club history that the club did not have a player-manager.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed Tony Mullane to a contract.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane, who spent the 1884 season with the Toledo Blue Stockings, had a 36–26 record with a 2.52 ERA in 67 starts, striking out 325 batters.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane was suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, as the Blue Stockings and the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons, another team he tried to sign with, folded after the 1884 season, and the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns attempted to reclaim Mullane, as he pitched there in 1883.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the Browns could reclaim him, he signed with the Red Stockings.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Frank Fennelly, who the Red Stockings acquired late in the 1884 season from the Washington Nationals, had a breakout season, hitting .273 with ten home runs and a league high 89 RBI.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones led the team with a .322 average, and had five home runs and 35 RBI to go along with it, while John Reilly hit .297 with five homers and 60 RBI.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Larry McKeon led the Red Stockings with 20 wins and a 2.86 ERA in 33 starts, while Will White had eighteen wins and a 3.53 ERA in 34 starts.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season very well, putting up an impressive 16–8 record in their first 24 games to sit in second place in the league, two games behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then began to slump, as they would win only six of their next sixteen games to slip into third place, seven games behind the Browns.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On July 1, the Red Stockings acquired Jim Keenan and Larry McKeon, who both jumped from the Detroit Wolverines to join Cincinnati.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings improved with their new acquisitions in the lineup, as the team eventually moved back into second place, however, they were too far behind the Browns, and Cincinnati finished the season with a 63–49 record, good for second place, however, they were sixteen games out of first.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1887 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in second place in the American Association with a record of 81–45, 14 games behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Following a horrible 1886 season, in which the Red Stockings finished under .500 for the first time in team history, the team hired Gus Schmelz to become the new manager.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons of the National League in 1886 to a 43–79 record.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] He also managed the Columbus Buckeyes of the American Association in 1883, leading them to a 69–39 record and a second-place finish.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati signed George Tebeau to his first professional contract, and acquired Hugh Nicol from the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns in a trade with sent Jack Boyle and $350 to the Browns.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol hit .206 with 19 RBI and 38 stolen bases, as well as scoring 44 runs in 67 games in 1886.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly had a great season, as he hit .306 with a team high ten home runs and had 96 RBI, as well as 50 stolen bases.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill led the club with a .311 batting average, and his 97 RBI tied him with Frank Fennelly for the team high.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol led the American Association with 138 stolen bases.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Mike Smith emerged as the ace of the staff, as he had a 34–17 record and a league best 2.94 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Tony Mullane also had a solid season, as he had a 31–17 record with a 3.24 ERA in 48 starts.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got off to a fast start, winning their first five games, however, Cincinnati lost six of their next seven games to fall to 6–6.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a 21–22 record after 43 games, before winning nine of ten to rise up to third place with a 30–23 record.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] After going 3–6 in their next nine games, Cincinnati had a season-high ten-game winning streak.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they remained in third place, 8.5 games behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings continued to play good baseball for the remainder of the season, as they finished the year in second place with a record of 81–54, fourteen games behind the first-place Browns.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1936 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fifth in the National League with a record of 74–80, 18 games behind the New York Giants.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] On November 22, 1935, the Reds signed free agent centerfielder Hub Walker.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Walker saw limited action with the Detroit Tigers in 1935, batting .160 with one RBI in only nine games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] With the Tigers AA affiliate, the Toledo Mud Hens, Walker hit .335 with 11 home runs in 113 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] On the same date, the Reds acquired first baseman George McQuinn from the New York Giants.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] McQuinn played with the Giants AA affiliate, the Newark Bears in 1935, hitting .288 with 11 home runs in 148 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] On December 12, Cincinnati purchased infielder Tommy Thevenow from the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Thevenow hit .238 with 47 RBI in 122 games during the 1935 season, playing mostly at third base.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] His best season was in 1926, when Thevenow finished fourth in National League MVP voting when he batted .256 with two home runs and 63 RBI in 156 games for the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] He helped the Cardinals win the 1926 World Series over the New York Yankees with a .417 batting average with a home run and four RBI in seven games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds also purchased minor league pitcher Johnny Vander Meer from the Boston Braves.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Vander Meer had a 7-10 record with a 5.35 ERA in 24 games with the Scranton Miners of the New York-Penn League.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds sold infielder Billy Sullivan to the Cleveland Indians on January 29.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Sullivan hit .266 with two home runs and 36 RBI with the Reds during the 1935 season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds held spring training at San Juan, Puerto Rico.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened camp at San Juan on February 10, 1936.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] During spring training, the Reds traded first baseman Jim Bottomley to the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Browns for infielder Johnny Burnett.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Bottomley struggled with Cincinnati in 1935, hitting .258 with one home run and 49 RBI in 107 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Burnett hit .223 with 26 RBI in 70 games in his first season with the Browns, after spending the first eight seasons of his career with the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds had a solid start to the regular season, winning six of their first ten games to sit in second place in the National League, 1.5 games behind the pennant leading New York Giants.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Following the strong start of the season, Cincinnati lost nine of their next 13 games, dropping to 10-13 and slipping into fifth place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] On May 31, the Reds purchased pitcher Bill Hallahan from the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Hallahan, who had spent ten seasons with the Cardinals, had a 2-2 record with a 6.32 ERA with the club in 1936.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] In 1931, he led the National League with 19 victories.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] On the same date, Cincinnati sold pitcher Tony Freitas to the Cardinals.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Freitas had a 0-2 record with a 1.29 ERA in four games with the Reds.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a very solid month of June, as by the end of the month, the club had a record of 36-30, however, the Reds remained in fifth place, five games out of first place behind the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Cardinals and Chicago Cubs, who were tied for first place.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The club struggled in July, posting a record of 11-18 during the month, dropping their overall record under .500 to 47-48.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati was still in fifth place, but was now 11.5 games out of first.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] On August 2, the Reds traded pitcher Si Johnson to the St.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Cardinals for pitcher Bill Walker.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Johnson, who had played with Cincinnati since 1928, appeared in only two games with the Reds in 1936.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] He played most of his games with the Reds AA affiliate, the Toronto Maple Leafs, where he posted a 10-9 record with a 2.38 ERA in 26 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Walker posted a 5-5 record with a 5.50 ERA in 19 games with the Cardinals in 1936.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds assigned Walker to Toronto for the remainder of the season.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Walker had previously pitched with the New York Giants, where he led the NL with the lowest ERA in 1929 at 3.09, and again in 1931 at 2.26.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati continued to struggle in August, as by the end of the month, the club had a 60-65 record, remaining in fifth place, but falling to 17.5 games out of first.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] During September, the Reds sent pitcher Bill Walker back to the Cardinals in an unknown transaction.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds had a strong start to the month of September, earning a 10-5 record in their first 15 games to reach the .500 mark.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] In the middle of the month, Cincinnati would go on a nine game losing streak, eliminating their chance of finishing above .500.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Overall, the club finished the 1936 season with a record of 74-80, 18 games behind the pennant winning New York Giants.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Offensively, the Reds were led by outfielder Kiki Cuyler, who in his first full season with the club, batted .326 with seven home runs, 74 RBI and 16 stolen bases in 144 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Ernie Lombardi led Cincinnati with a .333 batting average and 12 home runs, while driving in 68 runs in 121 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Ival Goodman hit .284 with a team high 17 home runs and tied Cuyler for the RBI lead with 74 in 136 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Rookie first baseman Les Scarsella hit .313 with three home runs and 65 RBI in 115 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Paul Derringer anchored the pitching staff, earning a record of 19-19 with a 4.02 ERA in 51 games played.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] His 282.1 innings pitched and 121 strikeouts led the Reds.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] Al Hollingsworth earned a record of 9-10 with a 4.16 ERA in 29 games, while Gene Schott had a record of 11-11 with a team best 3.80 ERA in 31 games.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The 74 victories and .481 winning percentage represented the Reds highest total since 1928, when they won 78 games and finished with a .513 winning percentage.
[src:1936-cincinnati-reds-season/1936-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds attendance of 466,345 was an increase of nearly 20,000 from the 1935 season, and was the highest since 1928, when the Reds drew 490,490 fans.
